node.text: Olive Oil Croissants for our special guests as we share a little preview of what’s to come at @DominiqueAnselWorkshop. Our croissant shop inside our pastry production kitchens officially opens next FRIDAY, JULY 16TH! And these are one of my favorites - we’re thinking about croissants differently here, so we developed these Olive Oil Croissants with cold-pressed extra virgin olive oil inside those flaky layers, and a bit of confit garlic and rosemary in the butter block during lamination  too. The result is a fragrant, slightly savory, beautifully golden croissant that’s just the slightest bit of green when you slice open to see that honeycomb crumb inside thanks to the verdant olive oil. Beautiful. I’m so grateful to have met so many of you and shared these with you even before we open our doors here in Flatiron. Can’t wait for opening day - we open at 8am on July 16th, so I hope to see you all here for 🥐🥐🥐.

Thank you to everyone who came out to visit and support us today for our round 1 of our @DominiqueAnselWorkshop First Batch taste testers, before we officially open our doors on Friday, July 16th. Today’s batch was our Brioche Bressane, a classic French pastry from the Bresse region made with fluffy light brioche filled with crème fraîche (our version is brushed with orange blossom water as soon as it’s out of the oven, then sprinkled with star anise powder and crunchy pearl sugar). 

We’ve read every single message submitted (yep, don’t worry, I’ve seen them), and we have one last First Batch handout next THURSDAY, JULY 8TH from 12pm-2pm.

Here’s how it works:

1. Follow us @DominiqueAnselWorkshop on Instagram
2. DM us @DominiqueAnselWorkshop by ‪Saturday 7/3 at noon‬ and answer one question: Why You? *For details on how we choose, head on over to @DominiqueAnselWorkshop

If you’ve already submitted a message to us the first time around, please know we’ve received it and are reviewing, so no need to re-submit. And if you haven’t submitted yet, please do! Those selected will be given the pick-up details and a secret password so you can claim your treats. Please note: those selected for this final round must be available to come claim your treats ‪on THURSDAY, JULY 8th between 12pm to 2pm.

See you all soon! 🥐

@Glenmorangie's newest whisky #ATaleofCake was inspired by a pineapple upside down cake, so I've decided to create my own version, with soft almond biscuit soaked in passionfruit whisky syrup, layered with juicy caramelized pineapple and creamy brown sugar ganache, all served up in a fresh pineapple. Try it here at the Bakery in Soho through October 6th only, but here's how you can make it at home.

Here's what you'll need for the caramelized pineapple, and check out https://bit.ly/2ElthU1 (link in bio⬆️) for the full cake recipe, including the brown sugar ganache.
 
CARAMELIZED PINEAPPLE
Ingredients:
1 ripe pineapple, peeled*
100g (1/2 cup) sugar
3g ground star anise
50g (1 2/3 oz) Glenmorangie A Tale of Cake
*NOTE: save the pineapple tops and outer peels so the cakes can be plated up and displayed as pictured*
 
Method:
1) Using a mandolin or sharp knife, slice 3mm thick slices of pineapple lengthwise (if you stand the pineapple straight up, you should be slicing downward around the core).

2) Make a dry caramel with sugar: sprinkle the sugar evenly into a medium pot, cook over medium-high heat until it caramelizes into a deep amber color.

3) Gently add in the pineapple slices, gently stirring to coat each piece (the pineapple juice will create a sauce with the caramel), and cook until just tender (don’t overcook, as the pineapple will turn mushy and fall apart). Add ground star anise and toss evenly.

4) Deglaze with the whiskey (be careful, as it may flame a bit). Cook for 30 seconds more, until the alcohol has cooked off but the fragrant whiskey flavor has infused.
 
#ATaleofCake #Glenmorangie #Whisky #SingleMalt #DrinkResponsibly #ad

Perfect as we get ready for autumn (and for Everyone Can Bake to launch in the UK September 3rd!). Sablé Breton topped w/ almond frangipane and fresh sliced apples - here's what you'll need:

SABLÉ BRETON
65g (4 large) egg yolks
130g (2/3 cup) sugar
125g (9 tbsp) unsalted butter softened
175g (1 1/2 cups) AP flour+more for dusting
11g (2 1/3 tsp) baking powder
1g (1/4 tsp) salt
Tools:
Stand mixer w/ whisk or hand mixer
8" cake ring, 2" tall
Silicone mat/parchment

1. In stand mixer w/ whisk (or bowl+hand mixer), whip yolks & sugar on high til fluffy 2-3 min. Add butter, whip to combine.
2. Fold in flour, baking powder, & salt w/ spatula til combined.
3. Transfer to large piece of plastic wrap. Form into square, wrap, refrigerate til firm, 2 hrs.

ALMOND FRANGIPANE
120g (8 tbsp) unsalted butter, room temp
110g (3/4 cup+2 tsp) powdered sugar
100g (2 large) eggs
15g (1 tbsp) rum
150g (1 1/2 cups) almond flour
250g (1 cup) pastry cream (recipe in book & a few videos back)
Tools:
Stand mixer w/ paddle or hand mixer
Piping bag

1. Make pastry cream, let cool.
2. Make almond cream: in stand mixer w/ paddle (or bowl+hand mixer), beat butter & powdered sugar on medium til fluffy 2-3 min. Add eggs & rum, beat til combined. Turn off, scrape sides of bowl. Add almond flour, beat til combined.
3. Remove pastry cream from fridge, mix w/ spatula til spreadable. Fold into almond cream w/ spatula til combined. Transfer to piping bag.

CARAMELIZED APPLES
4 Gala/Honeycrisp apples, peeled, cored, cut into 8 wedges
100g (1/2 cup) sugar
2 tbsp unsalted butter

1. Make dry caramel: heat nonstick pan over med-high heat. When hot, sprinkle sugar in even layer. Cook, remove from heat occasionally & swirl to avoid burning, til sugar is blond, 1-2 min.
2. Lower heat to med, add apples. Cook 1 min, flip, cook 1 min. Add butter to deglaze pan, swirl to coat slices. Cool 15 min.

ASSEMBLE
1. Preheat oven to 350F (175C).
2. Flour work surface. Roll chilled dough to size of ring mold, 1/2" thick. Use ring to cut into disc, transfer to baking sheet w/ silicone mat or parchment. Pipe thin layer of frangipane, stop 1/2" from edge. Add apple slices, bake 20-30 min. Cool 15 min, remove ring, enjoy!

Happy weekend! Today, I wanted to show you something savory for a change. People always ask me what my favorite comfort foods are. And this Croque Monsieur is definitely one of them. When I was an apprentice in France, my chef taught me this secret trick which I still use more than 20 years later: soak the bread in a savory custard first (almost like a savory French toast), so the sandwich stays nice and moist in the center while it toasts up in the oven, with those crispy edges and plenty of melted Gruyère cheese. Here’s what you’ll need: 

Equipment:
Pot
Spatula
Whisk
Mixing bowl
Baking sheet
Parchment paper

For the béchamel:
1 tbsp unsalted butter
7 tsp AP flour
1 cup whole milk
1/3 tsp salt
1/3 tsp black pepper
1 cup shredded Gruyère cheese 

For the soak:
4 large eggs
2 cups whole milk
1/2 tsp salt

4 slices Black Forest Ham
4 slices sourdough bread

Yield: this recipe makes 2 sandwiches 

Method:
1. In a pot, melt the butter over medium heat. Add flour, stir to combine with a spatula and cook for 1-2 minutes to make a roux.

2. Gradually add in 1 cup of milk, whisking to combine with each addition until smooth. Cook for 2 minutes, while continuing to stir. Add salt and pepper, then fold in 1 cup of Gruyère with a spatula until combined. Set aside and let cool 10-15 min before assembling the sandwich.

3. Preheat oven to 375F. 

4. Make the custard soak: in a mixing bowl, combine eggs, 2 cups of milk, and salt. Whisk to combine. 

5. Dunk the sourdough bread slices into the custard soak (you want them to be moist but not too wet or soggy). Place onto a parchment-lined tray. 

6. Spread a layer of béchamel into a slice of the soaked bread. Top with a generous amount of Gruyère, then add two slices of Black Forest ham on top. Add another layer of béchamel, then more Gruyère, and top with the second slice of bread. Spread a layer of béchamel onto the top of the bread, and sprinkle with more Gruyère. Repeat with the second sandwich. 

7. Toast in the oven for 10-15 minutes until the Gruyère is melted and caramelized, and the edges of the bread are nice and crisp. Remove from oven, slice in half, and enjoy!

Happy 4th and happy weekend! Time to bake. This time, I wanted to show you how to make a simple silky Lemon Curd. I like to spoon this curd - when it's still a bit warm - onto sablé Breton cookies, but you can also use it to fill tarts and layer inside cakes. Use this same recipe to make lime and grapefruit curds too. It's all in my book, Everyone Can Bake (out now, link in bio). Here's what you'll need:

INGREDIENTS

3g (3/4 tsp) unflavored powdered gelatin
12g (2 1/4 tsp) cold water
3g (1 1/2 tsp lemon zest
95g (6 tbsp) fresh lemon juice*
115g (1/2 cup + 1 tbsp) granulated sugar
160g (3 large) eggs
105g (8 tbsp, or 1 stick) unsalted butter, cut into cubes, at room temperature
* No need to use a messy juicer: Roll the lemon on your work surface. Zest it first, then slice it in half crosswise. Set a strainer over a small bowl to catch any seeds, then, holding a lemon half over the strainer, simply stick a fork into the fruit and twist gently to extract the juice.

1. Dissolve the gelatin: Combine the gelatin and water in a small bowl and stir with a spoon until the gelatin has dissolved.

2. Make the curd base: Combine the lemon zest, lemon juice, and sugar in a medium saucepan and bring to a simmer over medium heat, stirring until the sugar has dissolved. Remove from the heat.

3. Temper the eggs: Whisk the eggs in a large bowl. While whisking, pour one-quarter of the curd base into the eggs and whisk to combine. Repeat with another quarter of the curd mixture. Pour the tempered egg mixture into the saucepan with the remaining curd base and whisk until smooth and combined.

4. Cook the curd: Cook the curd over medium heat, stirring continuously, until it starts to bubble, then whisk in the gelatin mixture. Remove from the heat and let cool until just warm.

5. Finish the curd: Add the butter to the curd and whisk until the butter is fully incorporated and the curd is silky and smooth. Let cool completely before serving.

Tip: The recipe for the Sablé Breton cookies is also in #EveryoneCanBake. 
(Photo by @evansungnyc)

Happy Weekend! A lot of you have asked for the IG Live video I did recently with @TanFrance where we made a Cherry Clafoutis (one of my favorite French desserts). Here it is! I hope you'll bake this at home now that sweet summer cherries are in season. Here's what you'll need:

INGREDIENTS
2 large egg yolks
3 large eggs
1 1/4 cups sugar
1/3 cup + 1 tbsp AP flour
1 1/8 tsp baking powder
1 cup whole milk
1 cup heavy cream
1/2 vanilla bean, split, seeds scraped (or 1/2 tsp vanilla extract)
4 tsp Kirsch (optional)
1 lb fresh sweet cherries, pitted

EQUIPMENT
Mixing bowl
Whisk
Spatula
9” Round Ceramic Pie Dish or Metal Cake Pan

1. Preheat oven to 350°F.
2. Butter & flour the baking dish: butter base, sides, & inside edges, pour in some flour, shake around until evenly coated. Tap out excess flour.
3. In large mixing bowl, whisk together egg yolks, eggs, & sugar til evenly combined.
4. Add flour & baking powder, stir til combined.
5. Add milk, cream, & vanilla, stir til combined. Stir in Kirsch (optional).
6. Spread cherries in even layer on bottom of prepared pan. Pour in batter til it reaches just under the top rim (this won't rise much). Bake til custard is just set, edges are golden, & a paring knife poked into the center comes out clean, about 40-55 min (NOTE: baking time will vary depending on how large/deep your dish is; check after 30 min if you have a smaller pan). Let cool 15-20 min. Dust w/ confectioners sugar, serve w/ vanilla Chantilly.

VANILLA CHANTILLY
(Recipe from my book, Everyone Can Bake)

INGREDIENTS
2 cups + 2 tbsp cold heavy cream*
1/4 cup sugar
1/2 vanilla bean, split, seeds scraped (or 1/2 tsp vanilla extract)
* NOTE: Make sure cream is cold. If room temp or warm, it won’t whip up.

EQUIPMENT
Whisk (or hand/stand mixer w/ whisk attachment)

1. In stand mixer w/ whisk attachment (or use a large bowl & hand mixer/whisk), combine cream, sugar, & vanilla. Whip til the cream holds soft peaks, 3-4 min. If whisking by hand, use a large metal bowl and steadily whisk for roughly 5 min til soft peaks.

#BakeYourHeartOut #everyonecanbake

Happy weekend! Time to bake one of my favorite desserts: pavlova. All it takes is two ingredients - egg whites and confectioners’ sugar - to make a Swiss meringue. Once baked, top it with silky whipped cream and juicy summer strawberries. 🍓 It’s all in my book, Everyone Can Bake (link in bio ⬆️). Here’s what you’ll need:

MERINGUE INGREDIENTS
270g (2 cups) confectioners’ sugar 
130g (4 large) egg whites

EQUIPMENT
Stand mixer w/ whisk attachment (I don’t recommend doing this by hand)
Digital thermometer
4-in ring mold w/ 2-in sides
Silicone mat (or parchment)

1. Preheat oven to 375°F (190°C). Line sheet pan w/ silicone mat or parchment. Place ring mold in center.

2. In stand mixer w/ whisk attachment, whip confectioners' sugar & egg whites on low til combined.

3. Fill a pot w/ about 3 in of water. Bring to a simmer over medium heat.* Set bowl over pot of simmering water. Heat egg white mixture, whisking continuously, til it reaches 113°F (45°C) on a digital thermometer, 3-4 min.* Remove from heat.*
/
* Make sure the bottom of the bowl doesn’t touch the hot water (the egg whites will scramble).
/
* It’s important to use a thermometer for meringues as it needs to be precisely monitored. (I didn’t have one at home, so I used the back of my finger to test, til the mixture was slightly hot to the touch (a bit hotter than body temp), smooth & free of lumps.)
/
*This is a Swiss meringue, which is cooked twice—first when heated over simmering water, then when baked. It has a thin, crunchy exterior, & depending on how long it bakes, the interior can be crunchy or soft & moist.

4. Return mixer bowl to stand mixer. Whip the warm egg white mixture on high til stiff peaks & tripled in volume (5-7 min). 5. Scoop meringue into ring mold w/ a spatula, smoothing it to fill the edges. Carefully remove ring mold. (You can also free-form w/ a spatula into a 4-in wide X 2-in tall disc.) 6. Bake for 10 min. Lower oven temp to 325°F (163°C), bake for 20 min more til the outside is crisp & golden blond but the inside is still soft (it’ll spread a bit as it bakes.) 7. Let fully cool on sheet pan (don’t touch it, as it’ll deflate). Top w/ vanilla whipped cream & fresh berries.

Happy Weekend! It’s time to bake. Today, I wanted to share something that’s simple and comforting, and for me, there’s nothing more comforting that a fresh-baked chocolate chip cookie. A lot of you guys have asked for the recipe for our Chocolate Chunk Cookies that we serve at the Bakery, so here it is. My favorite part is the mix of dark and milk chocolate chunks, and of course, eating them while still warm from the oven. 😊 It’s one of recipes from my new book, Everyone Can Bake (link in bio ⬆️). Here’s what you’ll need:

INGREDIENTS
190g (14 tbsp) unsalted butter, at room temp
130g (2/3 cup) granulated sugar
130g (2/3 cup) packed light brown sugar
80g (2 large) eggs
330g (2 2/3 cups) AP flour
4g (1 tsp) baking soda
6g (1 tsp) salt
100g (2/3 cup) milk chocolate chunks 
100g (2/3 cup) dark chocolate chunks

EQUIPMENT
Mixing bowl
Spatula
Whisk
Baking sheet
Parchment paper

METHOD
1. Preheat oven to 350°F (175°C). Line a sheet pan with parchment paper.

2. In a large mixing bowl, combine butter, granulated sugar, and brown sugar with a whisk. Add the eggs and mix until incorporated.

3. Add the flour, baking soda, and salt. Mix until just combined with a spatula. Fold in the chocolate chunks until evenly distributed. Chill the dough for 5-10 min in the fridge.

4. Shape the chilled dough into balls about 2 1/2 in diameter, place them on the prepared sheet pan, and press down slightly to flatten them into discs.

5. Bake for 8-9 min, until the edges are golden and the center is soft and gooey. Let the cookies cool for 5-10 min until warm and then enjoy. (Once cooled, you can also make ice cream sandwiches with your favorite ice cream.)
#EveryoneCanBake (📸 by @evansungnyc)

Baking is a gift, and even now, there’s still lots of everyday occasions to celebrate! I’ve partnered with @KitchenAidUSA to #MakeItTogether to bring you this summer recipe: Strawberry Tiramisu. Just 3 components: ladyfingers, mascarpone whipped ganache & strawberry syrup (recipes below & in Everyone Can Bake). Share your work with me using #MakeItTogether because together, we can make baking all the more special. #ad

EQUIPMENT
KitchenAid Stand Mixer w/ whisk attachment
8x8 glass cake pan
Sheet pan

LADYFINGERS
8 large egg yolks
1⅓ cup sugar
8 large egg whites
2 cups flour
⅓ cup cornstarch
6tsp powdered sugar

1. Preheat oven to 400F. Line sheet pan w/ silicone mat/parchment.
2. In Stand Mixer w/ whisk attachment, combine yolks & ½ the sugar. Whip on high til fluffy, 3-5 min. Pour into large bowl.
3. Wash & dry mixer bowl & whisk. Whip whites on high til stiff peaks. Slowly add rest of sugar, mixing on high til combined.
4. Gently fold yolk mixture into white mixture w/ spatula til just combined. Fold in flour & cornstarch (don’t deflate the batter).
5.  Spread ½ the batter onto silicone mat into an even layer. Sprinkle w/ ½ the powdered sugar.
6. Bake til golden blond, 10-15 min. Let cool. Place parchment on top, invert pan, peel away silicone mat. Repeat w/ rest of batter. Slice into 3-4 squares to fit cake pan.

STRAWBERRY SYRUP
1-1.5lb fresh strawberries
½ cup sugar
Splash of Kirsch

1. Combine all ingredients in heatproof bowl. Cover w/ plastic. Place over double boiler for 35-45 min til syrup forms. Let cool 30 min. Strain, set aside.

MASCARPONE WHIPPED GANACHE
2½ tsp powdered gelatin
2 tbsp + 1¾ tsp cold water
1¾ cups heavy cream
1½ cups mascarpone
2¼ tbsp honey
5½ oz chopped white chocolate

1. Dissolve gelatin in bowl of cold water.
2. Boil cream, mascarpone & honey in pot over medium heat. Remove from heat, stir in gelatin mixture.
3. Place chocolate in heatproof bowl. Pour in ⅓ of the hot cream mixture. Wait 30 sec. Whisk til chocolate melts. Whisk in rest of cream til smooth. Cover w/ plastic, chill 2-3 hrs or overnight.
4. When ready to assemble tiramisu: transfer chilled ganache to Stand Mixer w/ whisk attachment. Whisk on high til fluffy 2-3 min

node.text: Happy Sunday and happy Mother’s Day! Time to bake. I thought I’d re-post this video that was shot with my friends at @munchies last year, when I made DKA’s (Dominique’s Kouign Amann) in their test kitchen. It’s an ambitious recipe that takes practice, but the results are so satisfying. The DKA, which is similar to a caramelized croissant, will always be my favorite pastry to make and to eat. I changed up the classic Breton pastry a bit with my own version, one that’s lighter and less heavy and sweet, and it’s something we started serving at the Bakery when we first opened (almost 2 years before the Cronut®). It takes fast and steady hands, but with practice, you’ll get the lamination down to achieve those flaky tender layers on the inside and a crunchy caramelized crust on the outside. Head to the Munchies website for the full recipe. Happy baking, everyone!

node.text: Son - your dad hasn’t slept more than 4 hours a night for multiple days with the new shop opening, but you’ve decided it’s time for a party. Still, every time I’d choose to stay awake and not miss these moments, and I’m glad I got to see your wobbly dance and over excited fist pump. Feeling energized all the same, despite knowing there’s half an hour less sleep tonight. (P.S. Celian, you say “aaah” when you want Alexa to play music, as in “ahhh lexa”. 🤣) #celianansel

node.text: TOMORROW! Our Soho Bakery pastry case is turning into our Summer Marché farmers market, filled with 9 different fresh fruit tarts. Think: white donut peaches, champagne mangoes, juicy rambutan, jam-filled red raspberries, Maradol papayas, golden apricots, and more. Available here in SoHo from Fri 7/23 to Sun 8/1. Preorders for a gift box of all 9 flavors are up at DominiqueAnselNY.com for pick-ups in-store. 🍓🍑🍒🥭🍋🍊#SummerMarche

node.text: What a difference a year makes. @dominiqueanselworkshop is now open in Flatiron, and as you enter, you’re welcomed by our beautiful croissant counter inside of our pastry kitchens. Swipe through for a look at how it all developed over the past year. Our thanks to my dear friend Gilles Depardon @ogawadepardonarchitects and his wonderful team for seeing the same vision as us, for pushing through all that we faced over the past year, and turning a blank 4,000 square foot white box into my dream kitchen and bakery space. A place for our chef team to work daily, a test kitchen for us to experiment with new ideas, and - at the center of it all - our beautiful croissant counter full of fresh-baked croissants and breakfast pastries for you all each day. Beautiful. 🙏

node.text: Meet our August Cronut® for NYC: Pineapple & Coconut, filled with pineapple mint jam and creamy coconut ganache. Tropical flavors for summertime here in SoHo. 😎 Starts August 1st in SoHo, preorders are up now at NYC.CronutPreorder.com for pick-ups.
